CHOLERA, DIARRHEA AND DYSENTERY UPDATE 2011 (35): (HAITI)
*********************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 10 Oct 2011
Source: Forbes.com, Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2011/10/10/general-cb-haiti-cholera_8727181.html


An aid official in Haiti says clinics in the capital are seeing a
worrisome jump in the number of cholera patients. Pascale Zintzen of
Doctors Without Borders says the number of weekly cholera cases has
jumped from about 250 more than a month ago to as many as 850.

Zintzen attributes the increase to Haiti's rainy season, which causes
the waterborne disease to spread freely. The number is still lower
than what officials documented at the epidemic's peak last November
2010.

Officials say the epidemic has since killed more than 6435 people and
sickened nearly 456 000 more.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The upswing of cholera cases in Haiti will continue until the end of
the current rainy season but the disaster of what is the sanitary
system in this country will perpetuate cases further. - Mod.LL]

[An interactive map of the cholera situation in Haiti is available
from HealthMap at http://www.healthmap.org/haiti/. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
